$$
\begin{aligned}
\phi^2 &= \left( \frac{\sqrt{5} + 1}{2} \right)^2
\text{ 1. Apply the exponent to both the numerator and the denominator.}\\
&= \frac{(\sqrt{5} + 1)^2}{2^2} 
\text{  2. Expand the numerator using the perfect square formula:} (a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2. \\
&= \frac{(\sqrt{5})^2 + 2(\sqrt{5})(1) + 1^2}{4} 
\text{ 3. Simplify the squared terms: } (\sqrt{5})^2=5 \text{ and } 1^2=1. \\
&= \frac{5 + 2\sqrt{5} + 1}{4} 
\text{ 4. Combine the rational terms (5 and 1)in the numerator.} \\
&= \frac{6 + 2\sqrt{5}}{4} 
\text{ 5. Factor out the common factor of 2 in the numerator.} \\
&= \frac{2(3 + \sqrt{5})}{4} 
\text{ 6. Cancel the common factor of 2 from the numerator and the denominator.}\\
&= \frac{3 + \sqrt{5}}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

